'''Yamatsuteru Shrine''' (山津照神社, ''Yamatsuteru-jinja'') is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Maibara City|ja|米原市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|ja|滋賀県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. It is a listed {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|2=ja|3=式内社|qq=draft|1=Shikinaisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with its former shrine Rank classified as a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} under the modern shrine Ranking system. The shrine's crest (''kamon'') features chrysanthemums and paulownias.

== deity ==
* {{ill|Kuninotokotachi no Mikoto|ja|国常立尊|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

== History ==
The shrine's founding date is unknown. It is recorded in the {{ill|Engishiki Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|2=ja|3=延喜式神名帳|4=zh|5=延喜式神名帳|6=simple|7=Engishiki Jinmyocho|ja|延喜式神名帳|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as a listed shrine (''shikinai-sha'') and is said to enshrine a divided spirit from {{ill|Hoyama Shrine|ja|帆山神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Echizen Province|ja|越前国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Historical records state that the shrine was awarded the sixth Rank (''Juroku-i'') in {{ill|Ninju|ja|仁寿|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1 (851 CE) and promoted to fourth Rank (''Jushi-i'') in {{ill|Jogan|ja|貞観|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 8 (866 CE).

In the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the shrine was designated a {{ill|Village Shrine|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 1881. It was later promoted to a {{ill|Prefectural Shrine|ja|県社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in 1921.

== Grounds ==
The shrine precincts include the {{ill|Yamatsuteru Shrine Kofun|ja|山津照神社古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, an ancient Kofun designated as a Shiga Prefectural Historic Site.
